window.EMPACT_DATA = {"manifest":{"id":"empact","title":"EMPACT — Emergency Medical Patients: Assessment, Care & Transport","subtitle":"The Ultimate Course Reviewer","version":"1.0.0","edition":"Systematic medical-patient assessment for EMS providers","description":"A comprehensive, self-contained study reviewer for the systematic assessment and management of the medical patient. Each chapter includes a concise summary, clinical pearls, red flags, common mistakes, memory aids, decision trees, high-yield flashcards, differential-diagnosis quiz questions, and realistic patient scenarios. Built for EMTs, paramedics, and nursing/PA students who need to move from possibilities to probabilities at the bedside.","icon":"stethoscope","color":"#1f6feb","accentColor":"#c8102e","estimatedHours":10,"difficulty":"Intermediate","certification":null,"examLink":"empact.html","audience":["EMT","AEMT","Paramedic","Nursing Student","PA Student"],"prerequisites":["Basic anatomy and physiology","BLS provider competency"],"contentTypes":["summary","flashcards","quizzes","scenarios","algorithms","tables"],"chapters":[{"id":"c01","number":1,"title":"The Systematic Approach & Differential Diagnosis","section":"Foundations","difficulty":"Beginner"},{"id":"c02","number":2,"title":"Airway Management in the Medical Patient","section":"Airway & Breathing","difficulty":"Intermediate"},{"id":"c03","number":3,"title":"Respiratory Emergencies","section":"Airway & Breathing","difficulty":"Intermediate"},{"id":"c04","number":4,"title":"Cardiovascular Emergencies","section":"Cardiovascular","difficulty":"Advanced"},{"id":"c05","number":5,"title":"Shock Recognition & Management","section":"Cardiovascular","difficulty":"Advanced"},{"id":"c06","number":6,"title":"Neurological Emergencies","section":"Neurological","difficulty":"Intermediate"},{"id":"c07","number":7,"title":"Endocrine Emergencies","section":"Metabolic","difficulty":"Intermediate"},{"id":"c08","number":8,"title":"Abdominal & Gastrointestinal Emergencies","section":"Abdominal","difficulty":"Intermediate"},{"id":"c09","number":9,"title":"Infectious Disease, Sepsis & Anaphylaxis","section":"Immune & Infectious","difficulty":"Intermediate"},{"id":"c10","number":10,"title":"Oncologic & Special Medical Considerations","section":"Special Topics","difficulty":"Intermediate"}]},"chapters":{"c01":{"id":"c01","title":"The Systematic Approach & Differential Diagnosis","shortTitle":"Systematic Approach","estimatedStudyTime":28,"difficulty":"Beginner","learningObjectives":["Describe the four stages of patient assessment: scene size-up, primary assessment, secondary assessment, reassessment.","Explain the concept of differential diagnosis as moving from possibilities to probabilities.","State the relative contribution of history versus physical exam in the medical patient.","Explain why life threats are identified and treated before a detailed history is taken.","Describe scene safety considerations specific to medical calls.","Explain why activities of daily living (ADLs) matter in medical assessment."],"summary":[{"title":"Differential Diagnosis: Possibilities to Probabilities","content":"Differential diagnosis is the process of narrowing a wide field of possible causes for a patient's presentation down to the most probable one (or few) explanations. It is not about reaching a single certain diagnosis in the field — it is about building an organized list of what could be happening, then using the history, physical exam, and vital signs to raise or lower the likelihood of each possibility, so that treatment and transport decisions are appropriately targeted."},{"title":"The Four Stages of Assessment","content":"Assessment proceeds through four stages. Scene size-up: initial observations for safety, standard precautions, the nature of the illness, and clues to the cause, performed before patient contact. Primary assessment: forming a general impression, determining level of consciousness, and identifying and treating immediate life threats (airway, breathing, circulation) — this stage also sets the patient's overall priority. Secondary assessment: a focused or detailed history, physical examination, and vital signs. Reassessment: ongoing monitoring, repeated more frequently in unstable patients, tracking trends and response to treatment."},{"title":"History Dominates in the Medical Patient","content":"For the medical patient, approximately 80% of the diagnostic information comes from the history, and only about 20% from the physical examination — the reverse emphasis from many trauma presentations. This means a structured, unhurried history (chief complaint, history of present illness, past medical history, medications, allergies) is often the single highest-yield tool available in the field. Active listening — getting on the patient's level and asking follow-up questions — is what makes that history useful."},{"title":"Life Threats First, Always","content":"Regardless of how compelling the history sounds, the primary assessment's job is to identify and treat immediate threats to airway, breathing, and circulation before proceeding to a detailed history and exam. A patient in respiratory failure or shock needs intervention now, not a complete past medical history first. This ordering — treat what will kill first — is the organizing principle underneath every other assessment skill in this course."},{"title":"Scene Safety and Pattern Recognition on Medical Calls","content":"Medical calls carry their own scene-safety considerations: standard precautions against blood and body fluids, awareness of the environment (hoarding, aggressive family members, drug paraphernalia), and — critically — recognizing when more than one person at a scene has the same signs and symptoms. A cluster of similarly ill people is a red flag for a shared environmental or toxic exposure (carbon monoxide, a gas leak, a common food source) rather than several unrelated coincidental illnesses, and should prompt inquiry into a shared cause before entering blindly."},{"title":"Why People Call: Activities of Daily Living","content":"Patients and families often call EMS not because a specific diagnosis has changed, but because the patient's Activities of Daily Living (ADLs) — the ability to walk, eat, dress, toilet, or think clearly — have become altered by illness. Asking 'what is different today compared to your usual baseline?' surfaces this functional change and is often more revealing than asking for a self-diagnosis, especially in patients who cannot articulate their complaint precisely (young children, patients with dementia, non-verbal patients)."}],"clinicalPearls":["Differential diagnosis is going from possibilities to probabilities — not guessing a single answer.","Always identify and treat life threats first (Airway — Breathing — Circulation).","In the medical patient, about 80% of the information comes from the history and 20% from the physical examination.","Always trust YOUR exam — your own primary assessment and findings, not just what you're told.","The key to active listening is getting on your patient's level and asking follow-up questions.","If more than one person presents with the same signs and symptoms, inquire about a shared cause."],"redFlags":["Skipping the primary assessment's life-threat check to jump straight into history-taking.","Multiple patients at one location with the same symptoms — treat as a possible shared exposure until ruled out.","Discounting your own physical findings in favor of a chief complaint that doesn't match what you're seeing."],"commonMistakes":["Treating assessment as a single event instead of a continuous, four-stage process with reassessment.","Spending exam time on find-everything physical exams when the history would answer the question faster.","Asking closed yes/no questions instead of open-ended questions that invite the patient to describe their own experience."],"memoryAids":["Possibilities → Probabilities: that is what 'differential diagnosis' means.","Size-up, Primary, Secondary, Reassess — the four assessment stages, in order.","History 80%, exam 20% — for the medical patient, listen first.","ADLs changed = why they called: what's different today?"],"decisionTrees":[{"title":"The Four Stages of Patient Assessment","content":"Arrive on scene\n  → Scene size-up: safety, precautions, nature of illness, clues\n  → Primary assessment: general impression, LOC, identify/treat life threats (A-B-C), assign priority\n     → Life threat found: treat immediately before proceeding\n  → Secondary assessment: focused/detailed history + physical exam + vital signs\n     → Build differential diagnosis: possibilities → probabilities\n  → Reassessment: repeat, more frequently if unstable; track trends and response to treatment"}],"references":["National EMS Education Standards — Assessment domain (systematic patient assessment)","EMPACT clinical pearls collection — Core Concepts and Assessment"]},"c02":{"id":"c02","title":"Airway Management in the Medical Patient","shortTitle":"Airway Management","estimatedStudyTime":26,"difficulty":"Intermediate","learningObjectives":["List the indications for bag-valve-mask (BVM) ventilation.","Differentiate the use and contraindications of oropharyngeal (OPA) and nasopharyngeal (NPA) airway adjuncts.","Describe the correct positioning for a patient with vomit or blood in the airway.","Recognize stridor as a marker of upper airway obstruction requiring urgent action.","Explain how altered mental status changes airway risk and management priority."],"summary":[{"title":"When to Assist Ventilation: BVM Indications","content":"Bag-valve-mask ventilation is indicated for apnea, bradypnea (too slow to sustain adequate minute ventilation), inadequate tidal volume (shallow breathing that fails to move sufficient air despite a normal-looking rate), cyanosis, and altered mental status with poor respiratory effort. The decision to assist ventilations is not based on rate alone — a patient breathing 14 times a minute with minimal chest rise may need just as much support as one breathing 6 times a minute."},{"title":"Airway Adjuncts: OPA vs NPA","content":"An oropharyngeal airway (OPA) is used in unresponsive patients without a gag reflex; if a patient gags or resists the OPA, remove it — it is not tolerated with an intact gag reflex. A nasopharyngeal airway (NPA) is used in patients with an intact gag reflex or who are semi-conscious, since it is generally better tolerated. The NPA is contraindicated in suspected basilar skull fracture or significant mid-face trauma, where inserting a tube through the nasal passage risks intracranial placement — a consideration to keep in mind even on 'medical' calls that follow a fall."},{"title":"Positioning for Vomit or Blood in the Airway","content":"When a patient has vomit, blood, or other fluid in the airway — whether from a medical cause (seizure, decreased LOC, GI bleed) or trauma — turn the patient onto their side (recovery position, or a modified logroll if spinal precautions are needed) to allow fluid to drain out of the mouth rather than pool in the posterior pharynx or be aspirated. Suction is used to clear what positioning alone cannot manage, but positioning is the first, fastest response and should not be delayed while equipment is prepared."},{"title":"Stridor: A Red-Flag Sound","content":"Stridor — a high-pitched sound typically heard on inspiration — indicates a partial upper airway obstruction (above the vocal cords), and is a potentially life-threatening finding requiring rapid action. Causes range from anaphylaxis-related angioedema to epiglottitis, foreign body, or airway burns. Unlike lower-airway wheezing, stridor signals that the obstruction is proximal and can progress to complete obstruction quickly — this finding should escalate urgency and prompt preparation for advanced airway support."},{"title":"Altered Mental Status Changes Everything About Airway Risk","content":"A decreased level of consciousness removes the patient's own protective airway reflexes — the ability to cough, swallow, and maintain tongue tone. This is why altered mental status appears repeatedly as an airway-management trigger across many medical conditions (overdose, stroke, post-ictal state, metabolic derangement, sepsis): the underlying diagnosis may differ, but the airway risk and the need for positioning, suction readiness, and possible adjunct use is a common thread that must be assessed independently of the cause."}],"clinicalPearls":["Indications for BVM include apnea, bradypnea, inadequate tidal volume, cyanosis, or altered mental status with poor respiratory effort.","NPA is for patients with an intact gag reflex or who are semi-conscious; it is contraindicated in suspected basilar skull fracture.","For a foreign body in the airway such as vomit or blood, turn the patient onto their side to allow drainage.","Stridor indicates upper airway obstruction and is a potentially life-threatening finding requiring urgent action."],"redFlags":["New-onset stridor in any patient — treat as a rapidly evolving airway emergency.","Forcing an OPA into a patient who is gagging or biting down on it.","Delaying positioning/suction for an airway full of vomit while gathering equipment."],"commonMistakes":["Judging ventilation adequacy by respiratory rate alone rather than tidal volume and effort.","Inserting an NPA in a patient with suspected basilar skull fracture or significant facial trauma.","Assuming a 'medical' patient cannot have a contraindication to an airway adjunct that is usually taught in the trauma context."],"memoryAids":["BVM triggers: Apnea, Bradypnea, inadequate Volume, Cyanosis, Altered LOC with poor effort.","OPA = no gag. NPA = gag present, but not with a skull-base fracture.","Stridor = STOP and act — proximal airway trouble.","Vomit/blood in the airway: turn them, then suction."],"decisionTrees":[{"title":"Airway Adjunct and Ventilation Decision","content":"Assess breathing adequacy (rate, depth, effort, color, LOC)\n  → Inadequate (apnea/bradypnea/poor tidal volume/cyanosis/altered LOC with poor effort): assist with BVM\n  → Airway adjunct needed?\n     → No gag reflex (unresponsive): OPA\n     → Gag reflex present / semi-conscious: NPA\n        → Suspected basilar skull fracture or significant facial trauma: AVOID NPA\n  → Fluid/vomit/blood present: position on side (or logroll with spinal precautions) + suction\n  → Stridor present: treat as urgent upper-airway emergency, prepare for advanced airway support"}],"references":["EMPACT clinical pearls collection — Airway and Respiratory categories","National EMS Education Standards — Airway, Respiration, and Ventilation domain"]},"c03":{"id":"c03","title":"Respiratory Emergencies","shortTitle":"Respiratory Emergencies","estimatedStudyTime":30,"difficulty":"Intermediate","learningObjectives":["Recognize wheezing as the hallmark sign of asthma and describe first-line treatment.","Identify respiratory failure from a very slow respiratory rate with shallow, ineffective breaths.","Distinguish spontaneous pneumothorax presentation, especially in COPD patients.","Recognize pulmonary embolism's classic presentation.","Explain the relationship between sepsis, fever, and altered LOC in a respiratory-complaint patient.","Explain why hypoxia is a common thread across respiratory complaints."],"summary":[{"title":"Asthma and Wheezing","content":"Wheezing is the hallmark sign of asthma, produced by bronchospasm and airway inflammation narrowing the lower airways. When wheezing does not respond to a patient's home rescue inhaler, nebulized beta-2 agonists (such as albuterol) are first-line prehospital treatment. If bronchospasm is severe enough that air movement is markedly diminished, wheezing may actually become quiet ('silent chest') — a sign of critical obstruction, not improvement, and a marker of an even more urgent emergency."},{"title":"Respiratory Failure: The Silent Danger of Bradypnea","content":"Respiratory failure can be identified by a very slow respiratory rate (bradypnea) combined with shallow, ineffective breaths — a pattern that is easy to miss because the patient may appear calm rather than distressed. Unlike the visibly labored tachypneic patient, the bradypneic patient in respiratory failure is running out of reserve; this presentation demands immediate ventilatory support rather than reassurance that a 'slow, quiet' patient is stable."},{"title":"Spontaneous Pneumothorax in COPD","content":"Spontaneous pneumothorax commonly occurs in patients with underlying COPD, where weakened lung tissue (blebs) can rupture without any trauma. It presents with sudden shortness of breath, often with pleuritic chest pain, and on exam may show diminished or absent breath sounds on the affected side. Because these patients already have reduced pulmonary reserve, even a small pneumothorax can produce disproportionate respiratory distress."},{"title":"Pulmonary Embolism","content":"Pulmonary embolism typically presents with sudden-onset dyspnea and pleuritic chest pain, often with tachycardia and sometimes hemoptysis, in a patient with risk factors such as recent immobility, surgery, malignancy, or a history of clotting disorders. It is a key differential to consider whenever dyspnea and pleuritic chest pain appear suddenly without an obvious respiratory infection or asthma trigger, since it can rapidly progress to hemodynamic collapse."},{"title":"Sepsis Presenting as a Respiratory Complaint","content":"Sepsis is frequently associated with fever and altered level of consciousness, and can present initially as a respiratory complaint (tachypnea, hypoxia) when the source is pneumonia or another infection. Because sepsis's respiratory findings can mimic primary lung disease, always screen for fever, altered mentation, and a possible infectious source in any respiratory patient, especially the elderly or those with indwelling devices."},{"title":"Hypoxia as the Common Thread","content":"Hypoxia is a common problem across nearly all respiratory complaints, regardless of the specific underlying cause — asthma, pneumothorax, PE, pneumonia, or heart failure can all ultimately produce it. Supplemental oxygen and continuous pulse oximetry monitoring are therefore standard across this entire chapter's conditions, even while the specific differential diagnosis is still being narrowed."}],"clinicalPearls":["Wheezing is the hallmark sign of asthma; nebulized beta-2 agonists are first-line if home therapy hasn't worked.","Respiratory failure can be identified by a very slow respiratory rate (bradypnea) with shallow, ineffective breaths.","Spontaneous pneumothorax commonly occurs in COPD patients and presents with sudden shortness of breath.","Pulmonary embolism typically presents with sudden onset dyspnea and pleuritic chest pain.","Sepsis is frequently associated with fever and altered level of consciousness.","Hypoxia is a common problem with respiratory complaints."],"redFlags":["A 'quiet chest' in a known asthmatic — absence of wheeze can mean critical, not improving, obstruction.","A calm-appearing patient breathing very slowly and shallowly — respiratory failure, not stability.","Sudden pleuritic chest pain and dyspnea with risk factors for clotting — treat as possible PE until ruled out."],"commonMistakes":["Reassuring a bradypneic patient as 'calm' instead of recognizing impending respiratory failure.","Missing sepsis as the underlying cause of a 'pneumonia' respiratory presentation with fever and confusion.","Attributing sudden dyspnea only to anxiety without considering PE or pneumothorax."],"memoryAids":["Wheeze = asthma's hallmark; SILENT chest = worse, not better.","Slow AND shallow = failure, not calm.","COPD + sudden SOB = think spontaneous pneumothorax.","Sudden dyspnea + pleuritic pain = think PE.","Fever + altered LOC + respiratory complaint = think sepsis."],"decisionTrees":[{"title":"Respiratory Complaint Differential Approach","content":"Patient with dyspnea\n  → Wheezing present? → Consider asthma/COPD; nebulized beta-2 agonist if not improved by home therapy\n     → Wheeze becomes silent: WORSENING, escalate care\n  → Sudden onset + pleuritic pain?\n     → COPD history + diminished breath sounds one side: consider spontaneous pneumothorax\n     → Risk factors for clot (immobility, surgery, malignancy): consider pulmonary embolism\n  → Fever + altered LOC: consider sepsis (e.g., pneumonia source)\n  → Very slow, shallow breathing, calm appearance: RESPIRATORY FAILURE — assist ventilation now\n  → In all cases: apply supplemental oxygen, monitor SpO2, reassess frequently"}],"references":["EMPACT clinical pearls collection — Respiratory and Respiratory/Cardio categories","National EMS Education Standards — Respiratory emergencies"]},"c04":{"id":"c04","title":"Cardiovascular Emergencies","shortTitle":"Cardiovascular Emergencies","estimatedStudyTime":32,"difficulty":"Advanced","learningObjectives":["Apply the CBIGK mnemonic to chest pain assessment.","Recognize Beck's triad and cardiac tamponade.","Identify inferior, anterior, and posterior MI patterns on a 12-lead ECG.","Explain the role of a right-sided ECG when the standard tracing is non-diagnostic.","Differentiate cardiac tamponade from other causes of chest pain and dyspnea."],"summary":[{"title":"CBIGK: A Chest Pain Assessment Mnemonic","content":"CBIGK is a memory aid for key elements to assess in a chest pain patient: Chest pain characteristics, Blood pressure, Irregular pulse, Glucose, and Potassium. This mnemonic pulls together the vital signs and point-of-care findings most likely to change immediate management — for example, an irregular pulse may indicate a dysrhythmia complicating a cardiac event, and glucose/potassium abnormalities can both mimic and complicate cardiac presentations."},{"title":"Beck's Triad and Cardiac Tamponade","content":"Beck's triad — jugular venous distention (JVD), muffled heart tones, and hypotension — indicates cardiac tamponade, a build-up of fluid in the pericardial sac that compresses the heart and impairs filling. A classic setup is a patient undergoing chemotherapy who develops a pericardial effusion, presenting with dyspnea on exertion; the triad distinguishes tamponade from pneumothorax (which has absent breath sounds, not muffled heart tones) or straightforward pulmonary embolism."},{"title":"Localizing MI on the 12-Lead ECG","content":"ECG lead groups localize the area of myocardial injury. An inferior MI shows changes in leads II, III, and aVF. An anterior MI shows changes in V1 through V4. A posterior MI is often missed on a standard 12-lead because it shows as ST depression in V1–V4 (a mirror-image pattern) rather than the expected elevation — confirmatory posterior leads may be needed. Recognizing these patterns quickly focuses both field treatment decisions and the receiving facility's activation of cardiac resources."},{"title":"The Right-Sided ECG","content":"When a standard 12-lead ECG is non-diagnostic in a patient with a strong clinical suspicion for inferior MI, obtaining a right-sided ECG can reveal right ventricular involvement — important because right ventricular infarction changes fluid management (these patients are often preload-dependent and can worsen with nitrates or other vasodilators). A right-sided ECG is a targeted, inexpensive next step that changes treatment, not just an academic exercise."},{"title":"Distinguishing Cardiac Causes of Chest Pain and Dyspnea","content":"Chest pain and dyspnea share a differential that spans cardiac tamponade, MI, pulmonary embolism, pneumothorax, and pericarditis. Beck's triad points to tamponade; pleuritic pain with sudden dyspnea and risk factors points to PE; absent (not muffled) breath sounds with sudden dyspnea point to pneumothorax; positional chest pain worse lying flat and improved sitting forward points to pericarditis. Building this differential systematically, rather than anchoring on the most common cause, is what protects against missing the less common but immediately dangerous diagnosis."}],"clinicalPearls":["Know the mnemonic CBIGK (Chest pain, Blood pressure, Irregular pulse, Glucose, Potassium) for chest pain assessment.","JVD, muffled heart tones, and hypotension (Beck's Triad) indicate cardiac tamponade.","Inferior MI: leads II, III, aVF. Anterior MI: V1–V4. Posterior MI: ST depression in V1–V4 or confirmatory posterior leads.","If an ECG is non-diagnostic, try to obtain a right-sided ECG (to evaluate right ventricular involvement)."],"redFlags":["Beck's triad in a patient with a cancer or chemotherapy history — think tamponade, not just heart failure.","ST depression in V1–V4 without obvious elevation — consider posterior MI, not 'normal' ECG.","Giving nitrates to a hypotensive patient with suspected right ventricular infarction."],"commonMistakes":["Treating muffled heart tones and JVD as simple heart failure without considering tamponade.","Missing posterior MI because the standard 12-lead shows depression rather than elevation.","Skipping the right-sided ECG when the initial 12-lead is non-diagnostic but suspicion remains high."],"memoryAids":["CBIGK: Chest pain, Blood pressure, Irregular pulse, Glucose, Potassium.","Beck's Triad: JVD + muffled heart tones + hypotension = tamponade.","II, III, aVF = inferior. V1–V4 = anterior. Depression in V1–V4 = think posterior (flip it).","Non-diagnostic ECG + inferior suspicion → flip to the right side."],"decisionTrees":[{"title":"Chest Pain / Cardiac Assessment Approach","content":"Chest pain or cardiac-concerning complaint\n  → Assess CBIGK: Chest pain characteristics, BP, pulse regularity, glucose, potassium\n  → Obtain 12-lead ECG\n     → Inferior pattern (II, III, aVF): consider right-sided ECG if non-diagnostic or hypotensive\n     → Anterior pattern (V1-V4 elevation)\n     → Depression in V1-V4 without clear elevation: consider POSTERIOR MI\n  → JVD + muffled heart tones + hypotension: consider Beck's Triad → cardiac TAMPONADE\n  → Treat per findings; avoid nitrates if right ventricular involvement/hypotension suspected"}],"references":["EMPACT clinical pearls collection — Cardiology and Cardiology/ECG categories","National EMS Education Standards — Cardiovascular emergencies"]},"c05":{"id":"c05","title":"Shock Recognition & Management","shortTitle":"Shock","estimatedStudyTime":28,"difficulty":"Advanced","learningObjectives":["Distinguish compensated from decompensated shock.","Explain why keeping shock patients warm matters physiologically.","Describe the role of inotropic vasopressors in cardiogenic shock.","Recognize early (compensated) shock signs before blood pressure falls.","Explain why blood pressure is a late, not early, indicator of shock."],"summary":[{"title":"Compensated Shock: The Early Warning Signs","content":"In compensated shock, the body's compensatory mechanisms (tachycardia, peripheral vasoconstriction) are still maintaining blood pressure, even though perfusion is already inadequate. Pale skin, tachycardia, and tachypnea are signs of compensated shock — the patient looks and feels sick, but the blood pressure number itself may still look reassuring. Recognizing compensated shock from these subtler signs, before the blood pressure drops, is what allows early intervention."},{"title":"Decompensated Shock: When Compensation Fails","content":"Falling blood pressure is indicative of decompensated shock — the progressive stage where compensatory mechanisms can no longer maintain perfusion pressure. Altered mental status frequently accompanies this progression, reflecting inadequate cerebral perfusion. By the time hypotension is measured, the patient has already been in shock for some time; waiting for a low blood pressure reading to diagnose shock means the diagnosis comes late."},{"title":"Why Warmth Matters in Shock","content":"Keep shock patients warm by covering them with a blanket to prevent heat loss. Hypothermia in a shock patient worsens coagulopathy, impairs cardiac function, and shifts the oxygen-hemoglobin dissociation curve unfavorably — compounding the physiologic insult of shock itself. This is a simple, easily overlooked intervention with real physiologic benefit, not just comfort."},{"title":"Inotropic Vasopressors in Cardiogenic Shock","content":"Inotropic vasopressors (e.g., dopamine) are indicated for persistent hypotension in cardiogenic shock — shock caused by the heart's failure to pump effectively, as opposed to volume loss or vasodilation. Unlike hypovolemic shock, where fluid resuscitation is central, cardiogenic shock often cannot tolerate large fluid volumes without worsening pulmonary edema, making inotropic/vasopressor support the more central pharmacologic tool once the cause is identified as cardiac."},{"title":"Matching Shock Type to Management","content":"Shock is not a single entity — hypovolemic (fluid loss), distributive (vasodilation from sepsis, anaphylaxis, or neurogenic causes), cardiogenic (pump failure), and obstructive (mechanical, e.g., tamponade, tension pneumothorax) shock require different primary interventions. Recognizing which category applies, using history and exam clues (fever suggests septic, chest pain suggests cardiogenic, a known allergen exposure suggests anaphylactic), guides whether the immediate priority is fluids, vasopressors, epinephrine, or a mechanical fix like decompression."}],"clinicalPearls":["Pale skin, tachycardia, and tachypnea are signs of compensated shock — the blood pressure may still look normal.","Falling blood pressure is indicative of decompensated shock (progressive stage).","Keep shock patients warm by covering them with a blanket to prevent heat loss.","Inotropic vasopressors (e.g., dopamine) are indicated for persistent hypotension in cardiogenic shock."],"redFlags":["Waiting for hypotension to appear before recognizing and treating shock.","Giving large fluid boluses to a patient in cardiogenic shock without considering pump failure.","Leaving a shock patient uncovered and allowing heat loss to compound coagulopathy."],"commonMistakes":["Assuming a normal blood pressure rules out significant shock.","Treating all shock the same way regardless of the underlying category (hypovolemic vs distributive vs cardiogenic vs obstructive).","Overlooking passive rewarming as part of shock management."],"memoryAids":["Compensated shock: Pale, Fast pulse, Fast breathing — BP still 'normal.'","Decompensated shock: BP finally drops, mental status follows.","Blanket = treatment, not just comfort.","Cardiogenic shock: pump problem → inotropes/vasopressors, not big fluid boluses."],"decisionTrees":[{"title":"Recognizing and Categorizing Shock","content":"Suspicious presentation (pale, tachycardic, tachypneic)\n  → BP still normal? → COMPENSATED shock — treat now, don't wait for BP to fall\n  → BP falling + altered mental status? → DECOMPENSATED shock — aggressive intervention\n  → Identify shock category from history/exam:\n     Fever/infection source → distributive (septic)\n     Known allergen exposure, stridor/hives → distributive (anaphylactic) → epinephrine\n     Chest pain, cardiac history, pulmonary edema → cardiogenic → inotropes/vasopressors, cautious fluids\n     Bleeding/fluid loss → hypovolemic → fluid resuscitation\n     Tamponade/tension pneumothorax signs → obstructive → mechanical correction\n  → In all types: keep the patient warm (blanket) to prevent heat loss"}],"references":["EMPACT clinical pearls collection — Shock and Pharmacology/Shock categories","National EMS Education Standards — Shock recognition and management"]}},"flashcards":{"c01":{"chapter":"c01","cards":[{"id":"c01_fc01","question":"What is differential diagnosis?","answer":"The process of narrowing a wide field of possible causes down to the most probable explanation(s) — going from possibilities to probabilities.","category":"Core Concepts"},{"id":"c01_fc02","question":"What is the highest priority in the primary assessment?","answer":"Identifying and treating life threats first — airway, breathing, circulation — before proceeding to history and exam.","category":"Core Concepts"},{"id":"c01_fc03","question":"What roughly is the split between history and physical exam value in the medical patient?","answer":"About 80% of the information comes from the history and about 20% from the physical examination.","category":"Assessment"},{"id":"c01_fc04","question":"What does scene size-up include?","answer":"Initial observations for safety, standard precautions, the nature of the illness, and clues to the cause.","category":"Assessment"},{"id":"c01_fc05","question":"What does the primary assessment establish?","answer":"General impression, level of consciousness, identification/treatment of life threats (A-B-C), and the patient's overall priority.","category":"Assessment"},{"id":"c01_fc06","question":"What does the secondary assessment consist of?","answer":"History, physical examination, and vital signs.","category":"Assessment"},{"id":"c01_fc07","question":"What is reassessment and when is it done more frequently?","answer":"Ongoing assessment to track trends and response to treatment; done more frequently in unstable patients.","category":"Assessment"},{"id":"c01_fc08","question":"What is the key to active listening in a patient interview?","answer":"Getting on your patient's level and asking follow-up questions.","category":"Clinical Pearls"},{"id":"c01_fc09","question":"Why should you 'trust YOUR exam'?","answer":"Your own primary assessment and findings are the most reliable data you have — don't discount them in favor of a chief complaint that doesn't match what you observe.","category":"Clinical Pearls"},{"id":"c01_fc10","question":"What should you consider if multiple people at one scene share the same signs and symptoms?","answer":"A shared environmental or toxic cause (e.g., carbon monoxide, gas leak, common food source) rather than coincidental separate illnesses — inquire about a shared cause.","category":"Safety/Scene"},{"id":"c01_fc11","question":"What are Activities of Daily Living (ADLs)?","answer":"Basic functional activities — walking, eating, dressing, toileting, thinking clearly — whose alteration by illness is often why people call EMS.","category":"Assessment"},{"id":"c01_fc12","question":"What question surfaces an ADL-based functional change?","answer":"'What is different today compared to your usual baseline?'","category":"Assessment"},{"id":"c01_fc13","question":"In a conscious medical patient exam, what comes first — questions or physical exam?","answer":"Ask questions first, then perform a physical exam directed by the answers.","category":"Assessment"},{"id":"c01_fc14","question":"Why is history so valuable in patients who cannot self-diagnose (children, dementia, non-verbal patients)?","answer":"Asking about functional/ADL changes from baseline reveals what's wrong even when the patient cannot describe or name a specific complaint.","category":"Assessment"},{"id":"c01_fc15","question":"Why treat life threats before taking a full history?","answer":"A patient in respiratory failure or shock needs immediate intervention — a complete history can wait, but airway/breathing/circulation failure cannot.","category":"Core Concepts"}]},"c02":{"chapter":"c02","cards":[{"id":"c02_fc01","question":"List the indications for BVM ventilation.","answer":"Apnea, bradypnea, inadequate tidal volume, cyanosis, or altered mental status with poor respiratory effort.","category":"Respiratory"},{"id":"c02_fc02","question":"When is an OPA appropriate?","answer":"In unresponsive patients without a gag reflex.","category":"Airway"},{"id":"c02_fc03","question":"When is an NPA appropriate?","answer":"In patients with an intact gag reflex or who are semi-conscious.","category":"Airway"},{"id":"c02_fc04","question":"What is the NPA contraindicated in?","answer":"Suspected basilar skull fracture or significant mid-face trauma.","category":"Airway"},{"id":"c02_fc05","question":"What should you do if a patient has vomit or blood in the airway?","answer":"Turn the patient onto their side to allow drainage, then suction as needed.","category":"Airway"},{"id":"c02_fc06","question":"What does stridor indicate?","answer":"Upper airway obstruction — a potentially life-threatening finding requiring urgent action.","category":"Respiratory"},{"id":"c02_fc07","question":"Why can a normal-looking respiratory rate still require BVM support?","answer":"Because tidal volume and effort matter as much as rate — shallow breathing at a normal rate can still be inadequate.","category":"Respiratory"},{"id":"c02_fc08","question":"Why does altered mental status increase airway risk?","answer":"It removes protective airway reflexes (cough, swallow, tongue tone), raising aspiration and obstruction risk regardless of the underlying cause.","category":"Assessment"},{"id":"c02_fc09","question":"Why should an OPA be removed if the patient gags on it?","answer":"A gag reflex means the OPA is not tolerated and can trigger vomiting/aspiration — it's reserved for patients without a gag reflex.","category":"Airway"},{"id":"c02_fc10","question":"Is stridor more concerning than wheezing for airway obstruction location?","answer":"Stridor signals a proximal (upper airway) obstruction that can progress to complete obstruction quickly, unlike lower-airway wheezing.","category":"Respiratory"},{"id":"c02_fc11","question":"What causes can produce stridor?","answer":"Anaphylaxis-related angioedema, epiglottitis, foreign body, or airway burns, among others.","category":"Respiratory"},{"id":"c02_fc12","question":"Why should positioning come before waiting to set up suction equipment?","answer":"Positioning (turning the patient) is the fastest first response to drain fluid and should not be delayed while suction is prepared.","category":"Airway"},{"id":"c02_fc13","question":"Why is airway risk from altered LOC a 'common thread' across different diagnoses?","answer":"Overdose, stroke, post-ictal state, metabolic derangement, and sepsis can all cause altered LOC — the airway management priority is the same regardless of the underlying cause.","category":"Assessment"},{"id":"c02_fc14","question":"What is a modified logroll used for in airway management?","answer":"Turning a patient with vomit/blood in the airway onto their side to drain fluid while maintaining spinal precautions if trauma is suspected.","category":"Airway"}]},"c03":{"chapter":"c03","cards":[{"id":"c03_fc01","question":"What is the hallmark sign of asthma?","answer":"Wheezing.","category":"Respiratory"},{"id":"c03_fc02","question":"What is first-line prehospital treatment for asthma not responding to home therapy?","answer":"Nebulized beta-2 agonists (e.g., albuterol).","category":"Respiratory"},{"id":"c03_fc03","question":"What does a 'silent chest' in an asthmatic mean?","answer":"Critical airway obstruction with minimal air movement — a worse sign than audible wheezing, not an improvement.","category":"Respiratory"},{"id":"c03_fc04","question":"How is respiratory failure identified?","answer":"A very slow respiratory rate (bradypnea) with shallow, ineffective breaths.","category":"Respiratory"},{"id":"c03_fc05","question":"Why is bradypneic respiratory failure easy to miss?","answer":"The patient may appear calm rather than visibly distressed, unlike a tachypneic patient working hard to breathe.","category":"Respiratory"},{"id":"c03_fc06","question":"In which patient population does spontaneous pneumothorax commonly occur?","answer":"COPD patients, due to rupture of weakened lung tissue (blebs) without trauma.","category":"Respiratory"},{"id":"c03_fc07","question":"How does spontaneous pneumothorax present?","answer":"Sudden shortness of breath, often with pleuritic chest pain, and diminished/absent breath sounds on the affected side.","category":"Respiratory"},{"id":"c03_fc08","question":"What is the classic presentation of pulmonary embolism?","answer":"Sudden onset dyspnea and pleuritic chest pain, often with tachycardia; risk factors include immobility, surgery, malignancy.","category":"Respiratory/Cardio"},{"id":"c03_fc09","question":"What two findings should make you suspect sepsis in a respiratory patient?","answer":"Fever and altered level of consciousness.","category":"Respiratory"},{"id":"c03_fc10","question":"What is a common thread across almost all respiratory complaints?","answer":"Hypoxia — supplemental oxygen and pulse oximetry monitoring apply broadly.","category":"Respiratory"},{"id":"c03_fc11","question":"Why is a slow, shallow, 'calm' breathing pattern dangerous?","answer":"It can represent respiratory failure — the patient is running out of reserve, not stabilizing.","category":"Respiratory"},{"id":"c03_fc12","question":"What underlying source commonly causes sepsis presenting with respiratory symptoms?","answer":"Pneumonia or another infectious source, especially in elderly patients.","category":"Infectious Disease"},{"id":"c03_fc13","question":"What risk factors raise suspicion for pulmonary embolism?","answer":"Recent immobility, surgery, malignancy, or a history of clotting disorders.","category":"Respiratory/Cardio"},{"id":"c03_fc14","question":"Why does a COPD patient with even a small pneumothorax show disproportionate distress?","answer":"Their baseline pulmonary reserve is already reduced, so a small additional insult produces a larger clinical impact.","category":"Respiratory"},{"id":"c03_fc15","question":"What should you always screen for in a respiratory-complaint patient with fever and confusion?","answer":"Sepsis, with attention to a possible infectious source such as pneumonia.","category":"Respiratory"}]},"c04":{"chapter":"c04","cards":[{"id":"c04_fc01","question":"What does the CBIGK mnemonic stand for?","answer":"Chest pain, Blood pressure, Irregular pulse, Glucose, Potassium.","category":"Cardiology"},{"id":"c04_fc02","question":"What is Beck's Triad?","answer":"Jugular venous distention (JVD), muffled heart tones, and hypotension — indicating cardiac tamponade.","category":"Cardiology"},{"id":"c04_fc03","question":"What causes cardiac tamponade in a chemotherapy patient?","answer":"A pericardial effusion compressing the heart, sometimes as a complication of certain chemotherapy agents.","category":"Cardiology"},{"id":"c04_fc04","question":"Which ECG leads show an inferior MI?","answer":"Leads II, III, and aVF.","category":"Cardiology/ECG"},{"id":"c04_fc05","question":"Which ECG leads show an anterior MI?","answer":"Leads V1 through V4.","category":"Cardiology/ECG"},{"id":"c04_fc06","question":"How does posterior MI appear on a standard 12-lead?","answer":"As ST depression in V1–V4 (a mirror-image pattern) rather than elevation; confirmatory posterior leads may be needed.","category":"Cardiology/ECG"},{"id":"c04_fc07","question":"When should you obtain a right-sided ECG?","answer":"When the standard 12-lead is non-diagnostic, especially with suspected inferior MI, to assess right ventricular involvement.","category":"Cardiology/ECG"},{"id":"c04_fc08","question":"Why does right ventricular infarction change fluid/drug management?","answer":"These patients are often preload-dependent and can worsen (become hypotensive) with nitrates or other vasodilators.","category":"Cardiology/ECG"},{"id":"c04_fc09","question":"How does tamponade differ from pneumothorax on exam?","answer":"Tamponade shows muffled heart tones with JVD and hypotension; pneumothorax shows absent breath sounds, not muffled heart tones.","category":"Cardiology"},{"id":"c04_fc10","question":"Why is glucose part of chest pain assessment (CBIGK)?","answer":"Glucose abnormalities can mimic or complicate cardiac presentations and change immediate management.","category":"Cardiology"},{"id":"c04_fc11","question":"Why is potassium part of chest pain assessment (CBIGK)?","answer":"Potassium abnormalities can cause or worsen dysrhythmias and complicate a cardiac event.","category":"Cardiology"},{"id":"c04_fc12","question":"Why does an irregular pulse matter in chest pain assessment?","answer":"It may indicate a dysrhythmia complicating a cardiac event, affecting both diagnosis and treatment.","category":"Cardiology"},{"id":"c04_fc13","question":"What is the danger of giving nitrates without considering right ventricular infarction?","answer":"In a preload-dependent right ventricular infarction, nitrates can cause severe hypotension.","category":"Cardiology/ECG"},{"id":"c04_fc14","question":"What historical clue raises suspicion for tamponade in a dyspneic patient?","answer":"A history of cancer/chemotherapy, which can predispose to pericardial effusion.","category":"Cardiology"}]},"c05":{"chapter":"c05","cards":[{"id":"c05_fc01","question":"What are the signs of compensated shock?","answer":"Pale skin, tachycardia, and tachypnea — blood pressure may still appear normal.","category":"Shock"},{"id":"c05_fc02","question":"What indicates decompensated shock?","answer":"A falling blood pressure — the progressive stage where compensatory mechanisms fail.","category":"Shock"},{"id":"c05_fc03","question":"Why keep shock patients warm?","answer":"Hypothermia worsens coagulopathy and impairs cardiac function, compounding the shock state — cover with a blanket.","category":"Shock"},{"id":"c05_fc04","question":"What are inotropic vasopressors used for in shock?","answer":"Persistent hypotension in cardiogenic shock (e.g., dopamine).","category":"Pharmacology/Shock"},{"id":"c05_fc05","question":"Why is blood pressure a late indicator of shock?","answer":"Compensatory mechanisms (tachycardia, vasoconstriction) maintain BP initially; by the time BP falls, the patient has been in shock for some time already.","category":"Shock"},{"id":"c05_fc06","question":"What accompanies decompensated shock's falling blood pressure?","answer":"Altered mental status, reflecting inadequate cerebral perfusion.","category":"Shock"},{"id":"c05_fc07","question":"Why can't cardiogenic shock be treated with large fluid boluses like hypovolemic shock?","answer":"The heart cannot pump effectively; excess fluid can worsen pulmonary edema instead of improving perfusion.","category":"Pharmacology/Shock"},{"id":"c05_fc08","question":"Name the four broad categories of shock.","answer":"Hypovolemic, distributive (septic/anaphylactic/neurogenic), cardiogenic, and obstructive.","category":"Shock"},{"id":"c05_fc09","question":"What clinical clue points toward septic (distributive) shock?","answer":"Fever and a likely infection source.","category":"Shock"},{"id":"c05_fc10","question":"What clinical clue points toward cardiogenic shock?","answer":"Chest pain, cardiac history, and possible pulmonary edema.","category":"Shock"},{"id":"c05_fc11","question":"What is the primary management focus for hypovolemic shock?","answer":"Fluid resuscitation to restore circulating volume.","category":"Shock"},{"id":"c05_fc12","question":"What is the primary management focus for obstructive shock (e.g., tamponade, tension pneumothorax)?","answer":"Mechanical correction of the obstruction (e.g., decompression, pericardiocentesis) rather than fluids or vasopressors alone.","category":"Shock"},{"id":"c05_fc13","question":"Why does recognizing the shock category matter for treatment?","answer":"Because fluids, vasopressors, epinephrine, and mechanical correction are not interchangeable — the wrong intervention for the category can worsen outcomes.","category":"Shock"},{"id":"c05_fc14","question":"Is a normal blood pressure enough to rule out significant shock?","answer":"No — compensated shock can have a normal blood pressure while perfusion is already inadequate.","category":"Shock"}]}},"quizzes":{"c01":{"chapter":"c01","questions":[{"id":"c01_q01","question":"What best describes the process of differential diagnosis in the field?","options":["A. Guessing the single correct diagnosis immediately","B. Narrowing a wide field of possible causes down to the most probable explanation(s)","C. Only ruling out cardiac causes","D. Waiting for hospital lab results before forming any impression"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Differential diagnosis is a process — moving from possibilities to probabilities using history, exam, and vitals — not a single instant guess.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c01_q02","question":"Which stage of assessment identifies and treats immediate life threats?","options":["A. Scene size-up","B. Primary assessment","C. Secondary assessment","D. Reassessment"],"correct":1,"rationale":"The primary assessment establishes a general impression, level of consciousness, and identifies/treats airway, breathing, and circulation threats, also setting patient priority.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c01_q03","question":"In the medical patient, approximately what percentage of diagnostic information comes from the history?","options":["A. 20%","B. 50%","C. 80%","D. 100%"],"correct":2,"rationale":"For medical patients, roughly 80% of the diagnostic information comes from the history, with about 20% from the physical exam — the reverse emphasis often seen in trauma.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c01_q04","question":"What should you do first when encountering a patient with an airway obstruction, before taking their full history?","options":["A. Ask about past medical history","B. Treat the airway threat immediately","C. Obtain a complete medication list","D. Perform a detailed head-to-toe exam"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Life threats are treated first, regardless of how much history remains to be taken — airway, breathing, and circulation problems are addressed immediately in the primary assessment.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c01_q05","question":"You arrive at an apartment and find three family members all reporting headache, nausea, and dizziness that began around the same time. What should you suspect?","options":["A. Three unrelated coincidental illnesses","B. A possible shared environmental/toxic exposure (e.g., carbon monoxide)","C. Anxiety spreading socially","D. Nothing unusual — treat each in isolation"],"correct":1,"rationale":"When multiple people share the same signs and symptoms, a common cause such as CO, a gas leak, or a shared food source should be suspected and investigated before entering blindly.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c01_q06","question":"What is included in the secondary assessment?","options":["A. Scene safety only","B. History, physical examination, and vital signs","C. Airway management exclusively","D. Transport decision only"],"correct":1,"rationale":"The secondary assessment gathers history, performs a physical exam, and obtains vital signs — building the data needed for the differential diagnosis.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c01_q07","question":"Why is reassessment performed more frequently in unstable patients?","options":["A. To satisfy documentation requirements","B. To track trends and detect deterioration or response to treatment promptly","C. It is not actually more frequent","D. Because unstable patients complain more"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Frequent reassessment in unstable patients catches trends — improving or worsening — allowing timely intervention changes.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c01_q08","question":"A family calls EMS saying their elderly father 'just isn't himself' but cannot name a specific complaint. What is the most useful question?","options":["A. 'Do you have chest pain?' only","B. 'What is different today compared to his usual baseline?'","C. 'What is his diagnosis?'","D. No further questions are needed"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Asking about functional change from baseline (ADLs) often surfaces the real problem, especially when the patient or family cannot self-diagnose.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c01_q09","question":"What does 'trust YOUR exam' mean in patient assessment?","options":["A. Ignore the patient's reported history entirely","B. Give weight to your own primary assessment and findings rather than discounting them in favor of a mismatched complaint","C. Only trust findings confirmed by a second provider","D. Physical exam findings are never reliable"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Your direct findings from the primary assessment are a critical, reliable data source — a mismatched or vague chief complaint shouldn't override what you actually observe.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c01_q10","question":"What is the correct order of the four stages of patient assessment?","options":["A. Primary, scene size-up, secondary, reassessment","B. Scene size-up, primary assessment, secondary assessment, reassessment","C. Secondary, primary, reassessment, scene size-up","D. Reassessment, scene size-up, primary, secondary"],"correct":1,"rationale":"The stages proceed scene size-up → primary assessment → secondary assessment → reassessment, each building on the last.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c01_q11","question":"Why does the key to active listening involve getting on the patient's level?","options":["A. It has no real effect on communication","B. It builds rapport and comfort, encouraging fuller, more accurate answers to follow-up questions","C. It is only a courtesy with no clinical value","D. It replaces the need for physical exam"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Physical positioning and engaged follow-up questions improve the quality and completeness of the history — the highest-yield tool in medical assessment.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c01_q12","question":"Which best explains why ADLs (Activities of Daily Living) matter in medical assessment?","options":["A. They are irrelevant to EMS calls","B. A change in ADLs (walking, eating, dressing, thinking) is often the actual reason a call was made, even without a named diagnosis","C. ADLs only matter for pediatric patients","D. ADLs replace the need for vital signs"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Patients and families frequently call because functional status has changed, not because a diagnosis was made — asking about ADL changes captures this directly.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c01_q13","question":"During assessment of a conscious medical patient, what is the recommended order?","options":["A. Physical exam first, then questions","B. Ask questions first, then perform a directed physical exam","C. Vital signs only, skip both history and exam","D. Simultaneously perform exam and questions with no particular order"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Given history's outsized diagnostic value in medical patients, asking questions first lets the subsequent physical exam be targeted and efficient.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c01_q14","question":"A crew skips checking for life threats and goes straight into a 10-minute history. What is the risk?","options":["A. None — history is more important than life threats","B. A time-critical airway, breathing, or circulation problem may go untreated while history is gathered","C. This is the recommended approach for all patients","D. It only matters for trauma patients"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Regardless of history's diagnostic value, life threats must be identified and treated first — delaying this for history-taking risks patient deterioration.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c01_q15","question":"Which scenario best demonstrates appropriate use of the differential-diagnosis approach?","options":["A. Assuming a single cause immediately and ignoring new exam findings","B. Building a list of possible causes, then using history/exam/vitals to raise or lower the likelihood of each","C. Never forming any clinical impression until arrival at the hospital","D. Diagnosing definitively in the field every time"],"correct":1,"rationale":"The differential-diagnosis approach is iterative: a list of possibilities is narrowed by evidence, not fixed on a single early guess or deferred entirely.","difficulty":"Hard"},{"id":"c01_q16","question":"What is the primary purpose of the scene size-up on a medical call?","options":["A. To begin taking vital signs early","B. To assess safety, apply standard precautions, and identify clues to the nature of the illness before patient contact","C. To determine transport destination","D. To complete documentation"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Scene size-up happens before hands-on patient care and focuses on safety, precautions, and situational clues — protecting the responder and informing the coming assessment.","difficulty":"Easy"}]},"c02":{"chapter":"c02","questions":[{"id":"c02_q01","question":"Which of the following is an indication for BVM ventilation?","options":["A. Normal rate and depth of breathing","B. Inadequate tidal volume","C. Mild anxiety","D. A patient who is talking in full sentences"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Inadequate tidal volume is a core BVM indication, along with apnea, bradypnea, cyanosis, and altered mental status with poor respiratory effort.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c02_q02","question":"A patient is unresponsive with no gag reflex. Which airway adjunct is appropriate?","options":["A. NPA","B. OPA","C. Neither is appropriate","D. Only an advanced airway"],"correct":1,"rationale":"An OPA is used in unresponsive patients without a gag reflex.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c02_q03","question":"A semi-conscious patient with an intact gag reflex needs an airway adjunct. Which is preferred?","options":["A. OPA","B. NPA","C. No adjunct can be used","D. Endotracheal tube only"],"correct":1,"rationale":"The NPA is generally better tolerated in patients with an intact gag reflex or who are semi-conscious.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c02_q04","question":"In which situation is the NPA contraindicated?","options":["A. Simple nosebleed","B. Suspected basilar skull fracture or significant mid-face trauma","C. Intact gag reflex","D. Semi-consciousness"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Suspected basilar skull fracture or significant mid-face trauma is a contraindication to the NPA due to the risk of intracranial tube placement.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c02_q05","question":"A patient having a seizure vomits during the postictal period. What is the immediate airway action?","options":["A. Insert an OPA immediately regardless of gag reflex","B. Turn the patient onto their side to allow drainage, then suction as needed","C. Sit the patient fully upright","D. Withhold any airway intervention until fully alert"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Positioning on the side allows vomit to drain out rather than pool or be aspirated; suction addresses what positioning alone cannot clear.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c02_q06","question":"What does stridor indicate?","options":["A. Lower airway bronchospasm","B. Upper airway obstruction","C. Normal breath sounds","D. Pleural effusion"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Stridor is a high-pitched sound indicating upper airway (proximal) obstruction, distinct from lower-airway wheezing, and is potentially life-threatening.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c02_q07","question":"A patient is breathing 14 times per minute but with minimal visible chest rise. What should you consider?","options":["A. Breathing is adequate since the rate is normal","B. Tidal volume may be inadequate despite a normal rate, warranting assisted ventilation","C. No further assessment is needed","D. This always indicates cardiac arrest"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Rate alone does not confirm adequate ventilation; poor tidal volume at a normal rate can still require BVM support.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c02_q08","question":"Why does altered mental status increase airway management priority across many different diagnoses?","options":["A. It doesn't — airway risk depends only on the specific diagnosis","B. Altered LOC removes protective airway reflexes (cough, swallow, tongue tone), regardless of the underlying cause","C. Only trauma patients with altered LOC have airway risk","D. Altered mental status has no bearing on airway management"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Loss of protective reflexes is a common risk factor across overdose, stroke, sepsis, and other causes of altered LOC — the airway priority is consistent even when the diagnosis differs.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c02_q09","question":"A patient bites down and gags on an inserted OPA. What should you do?","options":["A. Force it further in","B. Remove it — a gag reflex means the OPA is not tolerated","C. Leave it in place and proceed","D. Switch to a larger OPA"],"correct":1,"rationale":"An OPA is only for patients without a gag reflex; if gagging occurs, the OPA should be removed to avoid triggering vomiting or aspiration.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c02_q10","question":"Which finding should make you treat an airway complaint with the highest urgency?","options":["A. Mild wheeze on exhalation","B. New-onset stridor","C. A slightly elevated respiratory rate","D. A cough with clear sputum"],"correct":1,"rationale":"New stridor signals proximal airway obstruction that can progress to complete obstruction rapidly, requiring urgent escalation and preparation for advanced airway support.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c02_q11","question":"A fall victim with suspected basilar skull fracture needs an airway adjunct and has an intact gag reflex. What should you use?","options":["A. NPA, since gag reflex is present","B. OPA is not appropriate (gag present) and NPA is contraindicated (skull fracture); manage the airway by positioning/suction and consider other adjuncts per protocol","C. Force an NPA regardless of the fracture risk","D. No airway management is needed"],"correct":1,"rationale":"With an intact gag reflex, OPA is inappropriate; with suspected basilar skull fracture, NPA is contraindicated due to intracranial placement risk — positioning, suction, and other protocol-appropriate measures apply instead.","difficulty":"Hard"},{"id":"c02_q12","question":"Cyanosis in a breathing patient is significant because it suggests:","options":["A. Adequate oxygenation","B. Inadequate oxygenation, an indication to consider assisted ventilation","C. A normal finding in all patients","D. A skin allergy"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Cyanosis reflects inadequate oxygenation and is one of the listed indications for BVM ventilation.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c02_q13","question":"Which pairing is correct regarding airway adjunct selection?","options":["A. Gag reflex present → OPA","B. Gag reflex absent (unresponsive) → OPA; gag reflex present/semi-conscious → NPA","C. Both adjuncts are interchangeable regardless of gag reflex","D. Neither adjunct depends on gag reflex status"],"correct":1,"rationale":"OPA use requires absence of a gag reflex; NPA is chosen when a gag reflex is present or the patient is semi-conscious, as it is generally better tolerated.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c02_q14","question":"Why is stridor described as a 'red flag' finding rather than a routine respiratory sound?","options":["A. Because it is always benign","B. Because it indicates a proximal airway problem that can rapidly progress to complete obstruction","C. Because it only occurs in healthy patients","D. Because it requires no further action"],"correct":1,"rationale":"The proximal location of the obstruction causing stridor means airway compromise can worsen quickly, demanding urgent recognition and action.","difficulty":"Medium"}]},"c03":{"chapter":"c03","questions":[{"id":"c03_q01","question":"What is the hallmark sign of asthma?","options":["A. Stridor","B. Wheezing","C. Crackles","D. Absent breath sounds"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Wheezing, from bronchospasm and airway inflammation narrowing the lower airways, is the hallmark sign of asthma.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c03_q02","question":"A patient with a known asthma history has been using her rescue inhaler without relief. What is first-line prehospital treatment?","options":["A. Oral antihistamines","B. Nebulized beta-2 agonists","C. Aspirin","D. IV antibiotics"],"correct":1,"rationale":"When home rescue inhaler therapy fails, nebulized beta-2 agonists (e.g., albuterol) are first-line prehospital treatment for asthma.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c03_q03","question":"A known asthmatic in severe distress suddenly has NO audible wheezing. What does this mean?","options":["A. The asthma attack has resolved","B. Critical airway obstruction with minimal air movement — a worsening, not improving, sign","C. The patient is fully compensated and stable","D. Nothing significant"],"correct":1,"rationale":"A 'silent chest' means airflow is so restricted that wheezing can no longer be generated — this is a marker of critical, worsening obstruction requiring urgent escalation.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c03_q04","question":"How is respiratory failure identified?","options":["A. A rapid respiratory rate with deep breaths","B. A very slow respiratory rate (bradypnea) with shallow, ineffective breaths","C. Normal respiratory rate and depth","D. Loud wheezing only"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Bradypnea combined with shallow, ineffective breathing is the classic pattern of respiratory failure, and can be deceptively easy to miss since the patient may appear calm.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c03_q05","question":"Why is a calm-appearing, slow-breathing patient potentially more concerning than a visibly labored, fast-breathing one?","options":["A. It never is more concerning","B. Bradypnea with shallow breaths can indicate the patient is running out of respiratory reserve — impending failure","C. Calm patients are always stable","D. Rate is irrelevant to ventilation adequacy"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Unlike the visibly distressed tachypneic patient, bradypnea with shallow breathing signals exhaustion and impending respiratory failure, which demands immediate ventilatory support.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c03_q06","question":"A COPD patient develops sudden shortness of breath and pleuritic chest pain with diminished breath sounds on one side, without trauma. What should you suspect?","options":["A. Pulmonary embolism","B. Spontaneous pneumothorax","C. Asthma exacerbation","D. Sepsis"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Spontaneous pneumothorax commonly occurs in COPD patients from ruptured blebs, presenting with sudden dyspnea, pleuritic pain, and unilateral diminished breath sounds — without any trauma.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c03_q07","question":"A patient recently immobilized after surgery develops sudden dyspnea and pleuritic chest pain with tachycardia. What is the leading concern?","options":["A. Simple anxiety","B. Pulmonary embolism","C. Asthma","D. Common cold"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Sudden dyspnea and pleuritic chest pain in a patient with clot risk factors (recent immobility, surgery) is the classic presentation of pulmonary embolism.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c03_q08","question":"Which two findings should raise suspicion for sepsis in a patient presenting with respiratory symptoms?","options":["A. Fever and altered level of consciousness","B. Normal temperature and full alertness","C. Wheezing only","D. Pleuritic pain only"],"correct":0,"rationale":"Sepsis is frequently associated with fever and altered LOC, and can present as a respiratory complaint when pneumonia or another infection is the source.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c03_q09","question":"What common physiologic problem underlies nearly all respiratory complaints, regardless of specific cause?","options":["A. Hyperglycemia","B. Hypoxia","C. Hyperkalemia","D. Hypertension"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Hypoxia is a common thread across asthma, pneumothorax, PE, pneumonia, and heart failure — supplemental oxygen and pulse oximetry apply broadly to this chapter's conditions.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c03_q10","question":"An elderly patient with an indwelling urinary catheter presents with tachypnea, hypoxia, fever, and new confusion. What should be strongly considered?","options":["A. Isolated asthma exacerbation","B. Sepsis, possibly from a UTI or pneumonia source","C. Simple dehydration only","D. Anxiety attack"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Fever plus altered LOC in a respiratory-complaint patient — especially elderly with an indwelling device — should prompt strong consideration of sepsis from a urinary or pulmonary source.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c03_q11","question":"Why can pulmonary embolism be mistaken for a primary respiratory infection?","options":["A. It cannot be mistaken for anything else","B. Both can present with dyspnea, but PE's sudden onset with pleuritic pain and clot risk factors should distinguish it","C. PE always presents with a cough and fever identical to pneumonia","D. PE never causes dyspnea"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Overlapping dyspnea symptoms make PE a key differential; the sudden onset, pleuritic pain, and risk-factor history help distinguish it from infectious causes.","difficulty":"Hard"},{"id":"c03_q12","question":"A COPD patient with a small spontaneous pneumothorax shows disproportionately severe distress. Why?","options":["A. COPD patients overreact to minor findings","B. Their baseline pulmonary reserve is already reduced, so even a small additional insult has a larger clinical impact","C. Pneumothorax is always mild in COPD","D. This is unrelated to COPD"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Reduced baseline reserve in COPD means a small pneumothorax can tip a marginal patient into significant distress, unlike in a patient with normal lung function.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c03_q13","question":"Which action applies broadly across nearly all respiratory emergencies in this chapter?","options":["A. Withholding oxygen until a definitive diagnosis is reached","B. Supplemental oxygen and continuous pulse oximetry monitoring","C. Immediate antibiotics for all patients","D. Avoiding reassessment until hospital arrival"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Because hypoxia is a common thread, oxygen therapy and SpO2 monitoring are standard supportive measures while the specific differential is narrowed.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c03_q14","question":"A patient's asthma wheeze becomes progressively quieter as she becomes more anxious and tired. What is the correct interpretation and action?","options":["A. Improvement — prepare for discharge","B. Worsening obstruction (approaching silent chest) — escalate treatment and prepare for advanced airway support","C. No clinical significance","D. A sign to stop bronchodilator treatment"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Progressively quieter wheeze in a tiring, anxious asthma patient suggests worsening obstruction toward a silent chest — treatment should escalate, not stop.","difficulty":"Hard"}]},"c04":{"chapter":"c04","questions":[{"id":"c04_q01","question":"What does the CBIGK mnemonic help you remember?","options":["A. Airway adjuncts","B. Key chest pain assessment elements: Chest pain, Blood pressure, Irregular pulse, Glucose, Potassium","C. Shock stages","D. Stroke scale components"],"correct":1,"rationale":"CBIGK organizes the vital assessment elements for a chest pain patient: Chest pain characteristics, Blood pressure, Irregular pulse, Glucose, and Potassium.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c04_q02","question":"A patient with breast cancer on chemotherapy presents with dyspnea on exertion, JVD, muffled heart tones, and hypotension. What is the most likely diagnosis?","options":["A. Pneumothorax","B. Cardiac tamponade","C. Simple anxiety","D. Asthma exacerbation"],"correct":1,"rationale":"JVD, muffled heart tones, and hypotension constitute Beck's triad, classic for cardiac tamponade — here likely from a chemotherapy-associated pericardial effusion.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c04_q03","question":"Which three findings make up Beck's triad?","options":["A. Fever, tachycardia, hypotension","B. Jugular venous distention, muffled heart tones, hypotension","C. Wheeze, stridor, cyanosis","D. Chest pain, diaphoresis, nausea"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Beck's triad — JVD, muffled heart tones, and hypotension — indicates cardiac tamponade.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c04_q04","question":"Which ECG leads correspond to an inferior MI?","options":["A. V1-V4","B. II, III, aVF","C. I, aVL","D. V5-V6"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Leads II, III, and aVF show changes in an inferior wall myocardial infarction.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c04_q05","question":"Which ECG leads correspond to an anterior MI?","options":["A. II, III, aVF","B. V1-V4","C. aVR only","D. Lead I only"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Leads V1 through V4 show changes in an anterior wall myocardial infarction.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c04_q06","question":"A 12-lead ECG shows ST depression in V1-V4 without obvious elevation elsewhere. What should you consider?","options":["A. A completely normal ECG","B. Posterior MI, which can appear as a mirror-image depression pattern in these leads","C. Right bundle branch block only","D. This pattern always means the patient is fine"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Posterior MI classically shows as ST depression in V1-V4 (mirror-image of the elevation that would appear on true posterior leads) rather than obvious elevation — a commonly missed pattern.","difficulty":"Hard"},{"id":"c04_q07","question":"When should you consider obtaining a right-sided ECG?","options":["A. Only in trauma patients","B. When the standard 12-lead is non-diagnostic, especially with suspected inferior MI","C. Never — it adds no useful information","D. Only after hospital arrival"],"correct":1,"rationale":"A right-sided ECG helps identify right ventricular involvement when the standard 12-lead is non-diagnostic and inferior MI is suspected, directly changing fluid/drug management.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c04_q08","question":"Why is right ventricular infarction clinically important to identify?","options":["A. It has no treatment implications","B. These patients are often preload-dependent and can become severely hypotensive with nitrates or other vasodilators","C. It always requires immediate surgery","D. It only matters for documentation"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Right ventricular infarction patients depend on adequate preload; giving nitrates or other vasodilators can precipitate dangerous hypotension.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c04_q09","question":"How does cardiac tamponade differ from pneumothorax on physical exam?","options":["A. They present identically","B. Tamponade shows muffled heart tones with JVD and hypotension; pneumothorax shows absent breath sounds instead","C. Pneumothorax always causes JVD and tamponade never does","D. Neither causes any exam findings"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Tamponade's hallmark is muffled heart tones with JVD and hypotension (Beck's triad); pneumothorax instead shows absent/diminished breath sounds on the affected side — a key distinguishing feature.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c04_q10","question":"Why is glucose included in the CBIGK chest pain assessment mnemonic?","options":["A. It is irrelevant to cardiac presentations","B. Glucose abnormalities can mimic or complicate cardiac presentations, changing management","C. It only matters for pediatric patients","D. Glucose testing replaces the need for an ECG"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Glucose abnormalities (hypo/hyperglycemia) can present with cardiac-like symptoms or complicate an actual cardiac event, so checking it is part of a thorough chest pain assessment.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c04_q11","question":"Why does an irregular pulse matter during a chest pain assessment?","options":["A. It has no clinical significance","B. It may indicate a dysrhythmia complicating the cardiac event and affecting treatment decisions","C. It only matters in pediatric patients","D. Irregular pulses are always benign"],"correct":1,"rationale":"An irregular pulse can signal a dysrhythmia (e.g., atrial fibrillation, ectopy) that changes both the differential and the immediate management plan.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c04_q12","question":"A patient with suspected right ventricular MI and borderline blood pressure is being considered for nitroglycerin. What is the concern?","options":["A. No concern — nitrates are always safe in MI","B. Nitrates can cause severe hypotension in preload-dependent right ventricular infarction","C. Nitrates are only dangerous in anterior MI","D. Nitrates have no effect on blood pressure"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Because right ventricular infarction patients depend on adequate preload to maintain cardiac output, nitrates (which reduce preload) can precipitate dangerous hypotension.","difficulty":"Hard"},{"id":"c04_q13","question":"A patient presents with sudden dyspnea. Which finding would point AWAY from cardiac tamponade and toward pneumothorax instead?","options":["A. Muffled heart tones","B. Absent breath sounds on one side","C. Jugular venous distention","D. Hypotension"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Absent/diminished breath sounds point to pneumothorax, whereas tamponade's hallmark exam findings are muffled heart tones, JVD, and hypotension (Beck's triad).","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c04_q14","question":"What is the practical value of systematically building a chest pain/dyspnea differential rather than anchoring on the most common cause?","options":["A. It wastes time in the field","B. It protects against missing a less common but immediately dangerous diagnosis, such as tamponade or PE","C. It is only useful for documentation, not patient care","D. It has no practical value"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Because chest pain and dyspnea share overlapping presentations across several dangerous diagnoses (tamponade, PE, pneumothorax, MI), a systematic differential approach catches conditions that anchoring on the most common cause would miss.","difficulty":"Hard"}]},"c05":{"chapter":"c05","questions":[{"id":"c05_q01","question":"Which findings are signs of compensated shock?","options":["A. Hypotension and bradycardia","B. Pale skin, tachycardia, and tachypnea","C. Normal skin color and normal heart rate","D. Bright red skin and bradypnea"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Compensated shock presents with pale skin, tachycardia, and tachypnea — the body is compensating and blood pressure may still be normal.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c05_q02","question":"What does a falling blood pressure indicate in a shock patient?","options":["A. Compensated shock","B. Decompensated (progressive) shock","C. Full recovery","D. Nothing significant"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Falling blood pressure marks decompensated shock, the stage where compensatory mechanisms have failed to maintain perfusion pressure.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c05_q03","question":"Why should shock patients be kept warm?","options":["A. For comfort only, with no physiologic benefit","B. Hypothermia worsens coagulopathy and impairs cardiac function, compounding shock","C. Warmth increases blood loss","D. It has no effect on outcome"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Covering shock patients with a blanket prevents heat loss, which otherwise worsens coagulopathy and cardiac function — this is a physiologic intervention, not just comfort.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c05_q04","question":"When are inotropic vasopressors like dopamine indicated?","options":["A. All types of shock equally","B. Persistent hypotension in cardiogenic shock","C. Only in hypovolemic shock","D. Only in anaphylaxis"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Inotropic vasopressors are indicated for persistent hypotension specifically in cardiogenic shock, where the heart's pumping ability is the underlying problem.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c05_q05","question":"Why is blood pressure considered a 'late' indicator of shock?","options":["A. It changes before any other vital sign","B. Compensatory mechanisms maintain BP initially, so by the time it falls the patient has already been in shock","C. Blood pressure never changes in shock","D. It is the first and most sensitive sign of shock"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Because tachycardia and vasoconstriction compensate early, blood pressure remains normal until compensation fails — making it a late, not early, marker.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c05_q06","question":"A trauma patient is pale, tachycardic, and tachypneic, but their blood pressure is 118/76. What is the correct interpretation?","options":["A. No shock is present because BP is normal","B. Compensated shock is likely present despite the normal blood pressure","C. This patient is stable and needs no further monitoring","D. These findings are unrelated to shock"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Pale skin, tachycardia, and tachypnea with a still-normal BP are the classic presentation of compensated shock — treatment should not wait for hypotension to develop.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c05_q07","question":"A patient in cardiogenic shock is given a large fluid bolus similar to what a hypovolemic patient would receive. What is the risk?","options":["A. No risk — fluids are always beneficial in shock","B. Worsening pulmonary edema, since the heart cannot pump the extra volume effectively","C. Immediate improvement in all cases","D. Fluids have no effect on a failing heart"],"correct":1,"rationale":"In cardiogenic shock, the pump itself has failed, so large fluid volumes can precipitate or worsen pulmonary edema rather than improve perfusion.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c05_q08","question":"Which shock category is suggested by fever and a likely infectious source?","options":["A. Hypovolemic","B. Distributive (septic)","C. Obstructive","D. Cardiogenic"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Fever with an infectious source points toward septic shock, a distributive shock category caused by pathologic vasodilation.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c05_q09","question":"Which shock category requires mechanical correction (e.g., decompression) rather than primarily fluids or vasopressors?","options":["A. Hypovolemic","B. Obstructive (e.g., tension pneumothorax, tamponade)","C. Septic","D. Anaphylactic"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Obstructive shock is caused by a mechanical problem (tamponade, tension pneumothorax) that requires a mechanical fix — fluids and vasopressors alone will not correct the underlying obstruction.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c05_q10","question":"What accompanies the falling blood pressure of decompensated shock?","options":["A. Improved mental status","B. Altered mental status from inadequate cerebral perfusion","C. No change in mentation","D. Increased urine output"],"correct":1,"rationale":"As perfusion pressure falls in decompensated shock, cerebral perfusion suffers, producing altered mental status alongside the hypotension.","difficulty":"Easy"},{"id":"c05_q11","question":"Why is it important to identify the SPECIFIC category of shock rather than treating 'shock' generically?","options":["A. All shock categories are treated identically","B. Fluids, vasopressors, epinephrine, and mechanical correction are not interchangeable — matching treatment to category matters","C. Category identification is only for documentation","D. Treatment never depends on the cause"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Each shock category has a different primary intervention; using the wrong one (e.g., large fluid boluses in cardiogenic shock) can worsen the patient's condition.","difficulty":"Hard"},{"id":"c05_q12","question":"A patient in shock is left uncovered on a cold ambulance floor during a long transport. What physiologic consequence is most likely?","options":["A. Improved cardiac function","B. Worsening coagulopathy and cardiac function from hypothermia, compounding the shock state","C. No effect on outcome","D. Faster recovery"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Allowing a shock patient to become hypothermic worsens coagulopathy and cardiac performance — keeping the patient warm is an active treatment step, not just comfort.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c05_q13","question":"Which statement about compensated vs decompensated shock is TRUE?","options":["A. Decompensated shock always precedes compensated shock","B. Compensated shock precedes decompensated shock as compensatory mechanisms progressively fail","C. They are unrelated stages","D. Blood pressure falls first in compensated shock"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Shock progresses from compensated (BP maintained, subtle signs present) to decompensated (BP falls, mental status affected) as the body's compensatory mechanisms are overwhelmed.","difficulty":"Medium"},{"id":"c05_q14","question":"A patient with known heart failure develops hypotension, cool extremities, and pulmonary crackles. Which shock category and initial management approach fit best?","options":["A. Hypovolemic shock — give a large crystalloid bolus","B. Cardiogenic shock — consider inotropic/vasopressor support and cautious fluid administration","C. Anaphylactic shock — give epinephrine","D. Obstructive shock — needle decompression"],"correct":1,"rationale":"Heart failure history with hypotension and pulmonary crackles suggests cardiogenic shock (pump failure), where inotropic/vasopressor support is favored over aggressive fluid boluses, which risk worsening pulmonary edema.","difficulty":"Hard"}]}},"scenarios":{"c01":{"chapter":"c01","cases":[{"id":"c01_s01","title":"Not Himself Today","presentation":"You are called to a home for an 84-year-old man whose daughter says, 'He's just not himself today.' He has no specific complaint, is alert but slower to answer than usual, and his vital signs are within his normal range.","vitals":{"hr":"76 bpm","bp":"134/82 mmHg","rr":"16 bpm","spo2":"97%","loc":"Alert, slower responses"},"question":"What is the most useful next question to ask?","options":["A: 'Do you have chest pain?' and nothing else.","B: 'What is different about him today compared to his usual baseline?'","C: No further questions are needed since vitals are normal.","D: Ask only about his medication list."],"correct":1,"explanation":"With normal vitals and no specific complaint, the change in ADLs/baseline function is the real clue. Asking what's different from baseline can surface subtle findings (early stroke, infection, metabolic change) that a single closed question would miss.","clinicalPearl":"Activities of Daily Living that are altered is often exactly why people call EMS — ask what's different today."},{"id":"c01_s02","title":"Three Sick at the Same Table","presentation":"You respond to a restaurant where three coworkers who ate lunch together are now nauseated, dizzy, and complaining of headache within the same 30-minute window. No trauma is involved.","vitals":{"patient1_hr":"98 bpm","patient2_hr":"102 bpm","patient3_hr":"94 bpm","symptoms":"Nausea, dizziness, headache in all three"},"question":"What should you specifically investigate?","options":["A: Treat each patient as an isolated, unrelated case.","B: Inquire about a shared cause — common food, a gas leak, or another environmental exposure (e.g., carbon monoxide) affecting all three.","C: Assume food poisoning and transport without further scene assessment.","D: Ignore the pattern since vitals are only mildly abnormal."],"correct":1,"explanation":"Multiple people with the same signs and symptoms at one scene is a red flag for a shared cause rather than coincidence. Investigating a common source (shared meal, gas leak, CO) protects both patients and responders before further exposure occurs.","clinicalPearl":"Same symptoms, same time, same place, different people — think shared cause, not coincidence."},{"id":"c01_s03","title":"History First, Then Hands","presentation":"A 55-year-old woman is conscious, alert, and reports intermittent chest discomfort over the past two days. She is calm, breathing comfortably, and hemodynamically stable on your primary assessment.","vitals":{"hr":"82 bpm","bp":"128/78 mmHg","rr":"16 bpm","spo2":"98%","loc":"Alert"},"question":"Given no immediate life threats, what is the recommended assessment sequence?","options":["A: Perform a full head-to-toe physical exam before asking any questions.","B: Ask a directed history (onset, quality, duration, associated symptoms) first, then perform a physical exam guided by her answers.","C: Skip the history since vitals are stable.","D: Transport immediately without further assessment."],"correct":1,"explanation":"With no primary-assessment life threats, the recommended approach is history first — it carries about 80% of the diagnostic value in medical patients — followed by a physical exam directed by what the history reveals, rather than an undirected full exam.","clinicalPearl":"No life threat found? Let the history lead the exam, not the other way around."}]},"c02":{"chapter":"c02","cases":[{"id":"c02_s01","title":"Slow and Shallow","presentation":"A 68-year-old man is found unresponsive after an apparent overdose. His respiratory rate is 6 breaths per minute, shallow, with cyanosis around the lips.","vitals":{"rr":"6/min, shallow","spo2":"82%","skin":"Cyanotic lips","loc":"Unresponsive"},"question":"What is the correct airway/ventilation management?","options":["A: No intervention needed since he is still breathing.","B: Begin BVM ventilation given bradypnea, inadequate tidal volume, and cyanosis; consider an OPA since he is unresponsive.","C: Wait for him to breathe faster on his own.","D: Insert an NPA only, with no ventilatory support."],"correct":1,"explanation":"Bradypnea, shallow (inadequate tidal volume) breathing, and cyanosis are all BVM indications. Since he is unresponsive, an OPA is appropriate if there is no gag reflex, supporting effective bag-mask ventilation.","clinicalPearl":"Rate, depth, AND color all factor into the decision to assist ventilations — cyanosis alone is enough to act."},{"id":"c02_s02","title":"Vomiting Mid-Seizure","presentation":"A 30-year-old woman is postictal after a generalized seizure and begins vomiting while still minimally responsive, lying supine.","vitals":{"hr":"104 bpm","rr":"18 bpm, irregular","loc":"Postictal, minimally responsive"},"question":"What is the correct immediate action?","options":["A: Sit her upright immediately.","B: Turn her onto her side to allow the vomit to drain, then suction as needed.","C: Insert an OPA while she is actively vomiting.","D: Wait for her to become fully alert before intervening."],"correct":1,"explanation":"Vomit in the airway calls for immediate positioning onto the side to allow drainage and reduce aspiration risk, followed by suction for anything positioning alone can't clear. Placing an OPA during active vomiting risks triggering more vomiting/aspiration.","clinicalPearl":"Turn first, suction second — positioning is faster than any equipment setup."},{"id":"c02_s03","title":"The New Sound","presentation":"A 4-year-old with a known bee-sting allergy was stung 10 minutes ago. She now has a harsh, high-pitched sound on inhalation, facial swelling, and increasing anxiety.","vitals":{"hr":"138 bpm","rr":"28 bpm, harsh inspiratory sound","loc":"Anxious, alert"},"question":"What does this sound indicate and what is the priority?","options":["A: Normal breath sounds — reassure and monitor.","B: Stridor indicating upper airway obstruction (likely anaphylaxis-related angioedema) — treat as an urgent, rapidly progressing airway emergency.","C: Lower airway wheezing requiring only a bronchodilator.","D: A sound requiring no immediate escalation of care."],"correct":1,"explanation":"A new high-pitched inspiratory sound is stridor, signaling upper airway obstruction — here, likely angioedema from anaphylaxis. This is potentially life-threatening and can progress to complete obstruction quickly, requiring urgent treatment and readiness for advanced airway support.","clinicalPearl":"Stridor plus a known allergen exposure is an airway emergency in progress, not a wait-and-see finding."}]},"c03":{"chapter":"c03","cases":[{"id":"c03_s01","title":"The Quiet Chest","presentation":"A 22-year-old known asthmatic has been struggling to breathe for an hour, using his home inhaler repeatedly without relief. On your arrival he is exhausted, sitting tripod, and you notice his chest is now nearly silent on auscultation where it was loudly wheezing 10 minutes ago per his mother.","vitals":{"hr":"128 bpm","rr":"10 bpm, shallow","spo2":"88%","loc":"Exhausted, minimal responses"},"question":"What does the disappearance of wheezing mean, and what should you do?","options":["A: He is improving — no further treatment needed.","B: A silent chest means critical obstruction with minimal air movement — escalate treatment aggressively and prepare for advanced airway/ventilatory support.","C: The absence of wheezing rules out asthma.","D: Discontinue oxygen since he appears calmer."],"correct":1,"explanation":"A silent chest in a severe asthmatic is a critical sign — airflow has dropped so low that wheezing can no longer be generated. Combined with his exhaustion, falling SpO2, and slow shallow breathing, this is impending respiratory failure requiring aggressive treatment and ventilatory support readiness.","clinicalPearl":"In severe asthma, silence is not golden — a silent chest is worse than a loud wheeze."},{"id":"c03_s02","title":"Calm but Failing","presentation":"A 74-year-old man with COPD is found sitting quietly, breathing 8 times per minute with very shallow chest movement. He is not distressed-appearing but is slow to respond to questions.","vitals":{"hr":"92 bpm","rr":"8 bpm, shallow","spo2":"84%","loc":"Slow responses"},"question":"How should this presentation be interpreted?","options":["A: He is stable because he appears calm.","B: Bradypnea with shallow, ineffective breathing indicates respiratory failure — begin assisted ventilation.","C: This is a normal finding for COPD patients.","D: No intervention is needed since he is not gasping for air."],"correct":1,"explanation":"Calm appearance is deceptive here — the slow rate and shallow depth reflect exhaustion and failing respiratory drive, the classic pattern of respiratory failure. This patient needs immediate ventilatory assistance, not reassurance.","clinicalPearl":"The dangerous respiratory failure patient is often the quiet one, not the one gasping loudly."},{"id":"c03_s03","title":"Sudden Pain After the Flight","presentation":"A 45-year-old woman returns from a 12-hour international flight and develops sudden shortness of breath and sharp chest pain that worsens with deep breaths, with a resting heart rate of 118.","vitals":{"hr":"118 bpm","rr":"26 bpm","spo2":"91%","pain":"Sharp, pleuritic, sudden onset"},"question":"What diagnosis should be strongly considered?","options":["A: Simple muscle strain from the flight.","B: Pulmonary embolism — sudden dyspnea, pleuritic pain, tachycardia, with a major risk factor (prolonged immobility).","C: Asthma exacerbation.","D: Anxiety attack, no further workup needed."],"correct":1,"explanation":"Sudden-onset dyspnea with pleuritic chest pain, tachycardia, and a significant immobility risk factor (long flight) is the classic pulmonary embolism presentation. This diagnosis must be actively considered and can progress to hemodynamic collapse if untreated.","clinicalPearl":"Long flight, sudden pleuritic dyspnea, tachycardia — think PE until proven otherwise."}]},"c04":{"chapter":"c04","cases":[{"id":"c04_s01","title":"Shortness of Breath on Chemotherapy","presentation":"A 52-year-old woman undergoing chemotherapy for breast cancer reports recent-onset shortness of breath with exertion. Exam reveals jugular venous distention and muffled heart sounds.","vitals":{"hr":"118 bpm","bp":"88/62 mmHg","rr":"22 bpm","spo2":"93%","exam":"JVD, muffled heart tones"},"question":"What is the most likely diagnosis and what triad supports it?","options":["A: Pneumothorax, supported by absent breath sounds.","B: Cardiac tamponade, supported by Beck's triad (JVD, muffled heart tones, hypotension).","C: Pulmonary embolism, supported by pleuritic chest pain.","D: Pericarditis, supported by pain worse lying flat."],"correct":1,"explanation":"JVD, muffled heart tones, and hypotension are Beck's triad, classic for cardiac tamponade. Chemotherapy can cause pericardial effusion leading to tamponade. Pneumothorax presents with absent breath sounds instead of muffled heart tones, and this patient lacks the pleuritic pain typical of PE.","clinicalPearl":"A chemotherapy history plus Beck's triad should immediately raise tamponade on your differential."},{"id":"c04_s02","title":"The Non-Diagnostic 12-Lead","presentation":"A 61-year-old man reports crushing substernal chest pain radiating to his jaw. His initial 12-lead ECG is borderline/non-diagnostic, but his presentation strongly suggests an inferior MI, and his blood pressure is on the low side.","vitals":{"hr":"58 bpm","bp":"98/64 mmHg","rr":"18 bpm","ecg":"Non-diagnostic 12-lead"},"question":"What is the next best diagnostic step?","options":["A: Assume the ECG rules out MI and transport without further workup.","B: Obtain a right-sided ECG to assess for right ventricular involvement, especially given the relative hypotension.","C: Give nitroglycerin immediately regardless of blood pressure.","D: Repeat the same 12-lead in the identical position."],"correct":1,"explanation":"A non-diagnostic standard 12-lead with strong clinical suspicion for inferior MI — especially with relative hypotension — should prompt a right-sided ECG to evaluate right ventricular involvement, which would also caution against nitrate administration.","clinicalPearl":"Non-diagnostic ECG plus inferior-MI suspicion: flip to the right side before you flip through the differential."},{"id":"c04_s03","title":"Depression Instead of Elevation","presentation":"A 58-year-old woman with chest pain has a 12-lead ECG showing ST depression in V1 through V4, without clear ST elevation anywhere else. The crew initially considers the ECG unremarkable.","vitals":{"hr":"92 bpm","bp":"126/80 mmHg","ecg":"ST depression V1-V4"},"question":"What should this ECG pattern make you consider?","options":["A: A completely normal tracing — no further action.","B: Possible posterior MI, since it can present as a mirror-image ST depression pattern in V1-V4 rather than elevation.","C: Right bundle branch block with no ischemic significance.","D: An artifact requiring only lead replacement."],"correct":1,"explanation":"Posterior MI is a commonly missed pattern because standard anterior leads show ST depression (a mirror image of the posterior elevation) rather than the elevation clinicians expect to see. This ECG should not be dismissed as normal — posterior leads or additional workup are warranted.","clinicalPearl":"Depression in V1-V4 without a clear culprit elsewhere: flip your thinking to the posterior wall."}]},"c05":{"chapter":"c05","cases":[{"id":"c05_s01","title":"Normal Blood Pressure, Sick Patient","presentation":"A 35-year-old man involved in a motorcycle crash is pale, anxious, tachycardic, and breathing fast. His blood pressure is 116/74.","vitals":{"hr":"124 bpm","bp":"116/74 mmHg","rr":"26 bpm","skin":"Pale, cool"},"question":"How should this presentation be interpreted?","options":["A: No shock present since the blood pressure is normal.","B: Compensated shock — pale skin, tachycardia, and tachypnea indicate inadequate perfusion despite a still-normal blood pressure.","C: This is simple anxiety with no physiologic significance.","D: Wait until blood pressure drops before treating."],"correct":1,"explanation":"Pale skin, tachycardia, and tachypnea are the signs of compensated shock — the body's compensatory mechanisms are maintaining blood pressure even though perfusion is already compromised. Treating only once BP falls means treating late.","clinicalPearl":"A normal blood pressure doesn't mean a normal perfusion state — compensated shock hides behind normal numbers."},{"id":"c05_s02","title":"Heart Failure Patient Crashing","presentation":"A 70-year-old woman with a history of congestive heart failure presents with hypotension, cool extremities, and bilateral crackles on lung auscultation. She appears fluid-overloaded, not dehydrated.","vitals":{"hr":"104 bpm","bp":"82/58 mmHg","rr":"24 bpm","lungs":"Bilateral crackles"},"question":"What shock category is most likely, and what is the management concern?","options":["A: Hypovolemic shock — give an aggressive 2-liter fluid bolus.","B: Cardiogenic shock — favor inotropic/vasopressor support and avoid large fluid boluses, which could worsen pulmonary edema.","C: Anaphylactic shock — give epinephrine.","D: Obstructive shock — perform needle decompression."],"correct":1,"explanation":"A heart-failure history with hypotension, cool extremities, and pulmonary crackles points to cardiogenic shock. Because the heart's pumping ability is impaired, large fluid boluses risk worsening pulmonary edema; inotropic vasopressors (e.g., dopamine) are the more appropriate pharmacologic approach for persistent hypotension.","clinicalPearl":"Crackles plus hypotension in a heart-failure patient is cardiogenic shock, not a volume problem — don't fluid-bolus a failing pump."},{"id":"c05_s03","title":"The Overlooked Blanket","presentation":"A trauma patient in early compensated shock is being managed appropriately for bleeding and airway, but remains uncovered on a cold backboard during a 25-minute transport in winter conditions.","vitals":{"hr":"116 bpm","bp":"108/70 mmHg","temp":"Trending down, uncovered"},"question":"What additional intervention is being missed, and why does it matter?","options":["A: Nothing is missing — temperature is not a priority in shock.","B: The patient should be covered with a blanket; hypothermia worsens coagulopathy and cardiac function, compounding the shock state.","C: The patient should be given more oxygen instead of a blanket.","D: Warming has no physiologic effect during shock."],"correct":1,"explanation":"Keeping shock patients warm is an active treatment, not just comfort — allowing heat loss worsens coagulopathy and cardiac function, compounding the underlying shock physiology. A simple blanket is a meaningful intervention that is easy to overlook.","clinicalPearl":"In shock management, the blanket is a treatment, not an amenity."}]}},"algorithms":{"c01":{"chapter":"c01","algorithms":[{"id":"c01_alg01","title":"Systematic Patient Assessment Sequence","description":"The four-stage assessment framework applied to every medical patient encounter.","steps":["Scene size-up: assess safety, apply standard precautions, note the nature of the illness and scene clues before contact.","Primary assessment: form a general impression, determine level of consciousness, identify and treat life threats (airway, breathing, circulation), and assign patient priority.","Secondary assessment: obtain a directed history (history dominates in medical patients), perform a focused physical exam, and obtain vital signs.","Build and refine a differential diagnosis: move from possibilities toward probabilities using the gathered information.","Reassessment: repeat the key elements on an ongoing basis, more frequently if the patient is unstable, tracking trends and treatment response."]}]},"c02":{"chapter":"c02","algorithms":[{"id":"c02_alg01","title":"Medical Patient Airway Management Sequence","description":"Assessing and supporting the airway and ventilation in a medical patient.","steps":["Assess rate, depth, effort, color, and level of consciousness — not rate alone.","If apnea, bradypnea, inadequate tidal volume, cyanosis, or altered LOC with poor effort: begin BVM ventilation.","Select an adjunct: OPA if unresponsive with no gag reflex; NPA if gag reflex present or semi-conscious.","Avoid NPA if basilar skull fracture or significant mid-face trauma is suspected.","If vomit, blood, or fluid is present: turn the patient onto their side (or logroll with spinal precautions) and suction.","If stridor is present: treat as an urgent, potentially rapidly progressing airway emergency and prepare for advanced airway support."]}]},"c03":{"chapter":"c03","algorithms":[{"id":"c03_alg01","title":"Respiratory Complaint Differential Sequence","description":"A stepwise approach to narrowing the cause of a respiratory complaint while supporting oxygenation throughout.","steps":["Apply supplemental oxygen and continuous pulse oximetry regardless of cause — hypoxia is a common thread.","Assess for wheezing: if present and not improved by home rescue therapy, give nebulized beta-2 agonists.","Watch for a silent chest in a wheezing patient — this signals WORSENING obstruction, not improvement; escalate care.","Assess rate and depth: very slow, shallow breathing (bradypnea) in a calm-appearing patient indicates respiratory failure — assist ventilation immediately.","Consider spontaneous pneumothorax in a COPD patient with sudden dyspnea, pleuritic pain, and diminished unilateral breath sounds.","Consider pulmonary embolism in sudden dyspnea with pleuritic pain, tachycardia, and clot risk factors (immobility, surgery, malignancy).","Screen for sepsis (fever, altered LOC) as an underlying cause of a respiratory presentation, especially with a possible pneumonia source.","Reassess frequently and escalate ventilatory support as needed."]}]},"c04":{"chapter":"c04","algorithms":[{"id":"c04_alg01","title":"Cardiac Chest Pain Assessment Sequence","description":"A systematic approach to the chest pain patient using CBIGK and 12-lead interpretation.","steps":["Assess CBIGK: Chest pain characteristics, Blood pressure, Irregular pulse, Glucose, Potassium.","Obtain a 12-lead ECG promptly.","Identify inferior changes (II, III, aVF) or anterior changes (V1-V4).","If ST depression appears in V1-V4 without clear elevation elsewhere, consider posterior MI.","If the 12-lead is non-diagnostic but suspicion for inferior MI remains (especially with hypotension), obtain a right-sided ECG.","Check for Beck's triad (JVD, muffled heart tones, hypotension) — if present, consider cardiac tamponade.","Avoid nitrates/vasodilators if right ventricular involvement or hypotension is suspected."]}]},"c05":{"chapter":"c05","algorithms":[{"id":"c05_alg01","title":"Shock Recognition and Category-Matched Management","description":"Recognizing shock before hypotension develops and matching treatment to the underlying category.","steps":["Look for compensated shock signs even with a normal blood pressure: pale skin, tachycardia, tachypnea.","Do not wait for hypotension to begin treatment — falling BP signals decompensated (late-stage) shock.","Identify the shock category from history and exam: hypovolemic (bleeding/fluid loss), distributive (septic/anaphylactic/neurogenic), cardiogenic (pump failure), or obstructive (mechanical).","Match treatment to category: fluids for hypovolemic; epinephrine for anaphylactic; source control/fluids/antibiotics per protocol for septic; inotropes/vasopressors with cautious fluids for cardiogenic; mechanical correction for obstructive.","Keep the patient warm (blanket) throughout — hypothermia worsens coagulopathy and cardiac function.","Reassess frequently for progression from compensated to decompensated shock."]}]}},"tables":{"c01":{"chapter":"c01","tables":[{"id":"c01_t01","title":"The Four Stages of Assessment","headers":["Stage","Purpose","Key Actions"],"rows":[["Scene size-up","Protect responders; gather scene clues","Safety check, standard precautions, nature-of-illness clues"],["Primary assessment","Find and treat life threats","General impression, LOC, A-B-C threats, assign priority"],["Secondary assessment","Build the differential diagnosis","History, physical exam, vital signs"],["Reassessment","Track trends and treatment response","Repeat key elements; more frequent if unstable"]]},{"id":"c01_t02","title":"Diagnostic Value: History vs Physical Exam (Medical Patient)","headers":["Source","Approximate Contribution"],"rows":[["History","~80%"],["Physical examination","~20%"]]}]},"c02":{"chapter":"c02","tables":[{"id":"c02_t01","title":"Airway Adjunct Selection: OPA vs NPA","headers":["Feature","OPA","NPA"],"rows":[["Patient state","Unresponsive, no gag reflex","Gag reflex present or semi-conscious"],["Tolerance","Poor if gag reflex present","Generally better tolerated"],["Key contraindication","Intact gag reflex","Suspected basilar skull fracture / significant mid-face trauma"]]},{"id":"c02_t02","title":"BVM Ventilation Indications","headers":["Finding","Why It Matters"],"rows":[["Apnea","No spontaneous breathing"],["Bradypnea","Rate too slow for adequate minute ventilation"],["Inadequate tidal volume","Shallow breaths fail to move sufficient air, even at a normal rate"],["Cyanosis","Sign of inadequate oxygenation"],["Altered LOC + poor effort","Reduced drive/effort compounding ventilation failure"]]}]},"c03":{"chapter":"c03","tables":[{"id":"c03_t01","title":"Respiratory Emergency Differential at a Glance","headers":["Condition","Classic Presentation","Key Distinguishing Clue"],"rows":[["Asthma","Wheezing, dyspnea, prior triggers","Improves with nebulized beta-2 agonist; silent chest = critical"],["Respiratory failure","Slow, shallow breathing, calm appearance","Bradypnea + poor tidal volume"],["Spontaneous pneumothorax","Sudden dyspnea, pleuritic pain","COPD history; diminished unilateral breath sounds; no trauma"],["Pulmonary embolism","Sudden dyspnea, pleuritic pain, tachycardia","Immobility/surgery/malignancy risk factors"],["Sepsis (respiratory presentation)","Tachypnea, hypoxia, fever","Altered LOC; possible pneumonia/UTI source"]]},{"id":"c03_t02","title":"Wheeze Progression: What It Means","headers":["Finding","Interpretation"],"rows":[["Loud wheeze","Airway narrowing with some air movement"],["Wheeze quieting as patient tires/becomes anxious","Worsening obstruction — a warning sign"],["Silent chest","Critical obstruction, minimal air movement — most severe"]]}]},"c04":{"chapter":"c04","tables":[{"id":"c04_t01","title":"MI Localization by ECG Leads","headers":["MI Location","Leads Showing Changes","Notes"],"rows":[["Inferior","II, III, aVF","Consider right-sided ECG if non-diagnostic or hypotensive"],["Anterior","V1–V4","Often larger territory, higher-risk pattern"],["Posterior","ST depression in V1–V4 (mirror image)","Confirmatory posterior leads may be needed; easily missed"]]},{"id":"c04_t02","title":"Cardiac Tamponade vs Pneumothorax vs Pulmonary Embolism","headers":["Feature","Tamponade","Pneumothorax","Pulmonary Embolism"],"rows":[["Heart sounds","Muffled","Normal","Normal"],["Breath sounds","Normal","Absent/diminished (one side)","Normal (may have pleuritic pain)"],["JVD","Present","May be present (tension)","Usually absent unless massive"],["Blood pressure","Hypotension (Beck's triad)","Variable, hypotension if tension","Variable, can be hypotensive if massive"],["Classic trigger","Effusion (e.g., malignancy)","COPD/bleb rupture or trauma","Immobility, surgery, malignancy"]]},{"id":"c04_t03","title":"CBIGK Chest Pain Assessment Mnemonic","headers":["Letter","Element","Why It Matters"],"rows":[["C","Chest pain characteristics","Quality, onset, radiation, associated symptoms"],["B","Blood pressure","Hypotension changes drug choices (e.g., avoid nitrates)"],["I","Irregular pulse","May indicate a complicating dysrhythmia"],["G","Glucose","Can mimic or complicate cardiac presentations"],["K","Potassium","Abnormalities can cause/worsen dysrhythmias"]]}]},"c05":{"chapter":"c05","tables":[{"id":"c05_t01","title":"Compensated vs Decompensated Shock","headers":["Feature","Compensated Shock","Decompensated Shock"],"rows":[["Blood pressure","Normal (compensation intact)","Falling"],["Skin","Pale, cool","Pale/mottled, cooler"],["Heart rate","Tachycardic","Tachycardic (may become irregular/bradycardic terminally)"],["Respiratory rate","Tachypneic","Tachypneic or irregular"],["Mental status","Usually intact, may be anxious","Altered"],["Clinical significance","Perfusion already compromised despite normal BP","Compensatory mechanisms have failed"]]},{"id":"c05_t02","title":"Shock Categories and Primary Management Focus","headers":["Category","Cause","Primary Management Focus"],"rows":[["Hypovolemic","Blood/fluid loss","Fluid/blood resuscitation"],["Distributive — septic","Infection, vasodilation","Source control, fluids, antibiotics per protocol"],["Distributive — anaphylactic","Allergic vasodilation","IM epinephrine first-line"],["Cardiogenic","Pump failure","Inotropes/vasopressors; cautious fluids"],["Obstructive","Mechanical (tamponade, tension pneumothorax)","Mechanical correction (decompression, etc.)"]]}]}}};
